fact that this becomes really

01:18:07.910 --> 01:18:12.380
difficult. So when we
talk about the differences

01:18:12.380 --> 01:18:15.460
between the grassroots and
elite, one of the things

01:18:15.460 --> 01:18:18.700
that historians have done
over the past, let's say,

01:18:18.700 --> 01:18:22.680
20 odd years is introduced
what we call social history

01:18:22.680 --> 01:18:24.180
to the work of
political history,

01:18:24.180 --> 01:18:28.690
where we're looking
at the kind of work

01:18:28.690 --> 01:18:32.030
and the everyday
lives of activists.

01:18:32.030 --> 01:18:37.820
And so we're also finding
non-elite actors and the work

01:18:37.820 --> 01:18:40.410
that they're doing
in their homes

01:18:40.410 --> 01:18:44.090
that you're not going to read
about in the National Review,

01:18:44.090 --> 01:18:48.270
even though those activists
themselves are reading

01:18:48.270 --> 01:18:49.680
the National Review.

01:18:49.680 --> 01:18:56.320
But that's not what I
found in my research, Don.

01:18:56.320 --> 01:18:56.820
But--

01:18:56.820 --> 01:18:58.236
- I'm sorry,
[INTERPOSING VOICES].

01:18:58.236 --> 01:18:58.740
- Oh, OK.

01:18:58.740 --> 01:19:02.030
But in the 1950s, they were.

01:19:02.030 --> 01:19:04.440
But they were also
doing some things

01:19:04.440 --> 01:19:10.390
that elite political actors
would refer to as crackpot.

01:19:10.390 --> 01:19:11.810
They had some ideas.

01:19:11.810 --> 01:19:15.230
They were spinning
conspiracy theories.

01:19:15.230 --> 01:19:20.280
In fact, you might even call
it reactionism at the time.

01:19:20.280 --> 01:19:23.410
It was pretty populist.

01:19:23.410 --> 01:19:26.330
But yet they were very
important to the emergence

01:19:26.330 --> 01:19:29.040
of the John Birch Society
and the Goldwater Movement.

01:19:29.040 --> 01:19:33.800
So it's really hard to determine
who are the real conservatives

01:19:33.800 --> 01:19:39.440
and how do we decide whose
papers we need to place, right?

01:19:39.440 --> 01:19:42.100
And I'm not saying
that what I have to say

01:19:42.100 --> 01:19:44.130
about it is the most important.

01:19:44.130 --> 01:19:46.960
I just think that it's just
a little bit difficult.

01:19:46.960 --> 01:19:48.350
- This is a minor interjection.

01:19:48.350 --> 01:19:51.800
Even to recognize that those
different strands exist

01:19:51.800 --> 01:19:55.410
is a step in the
right direction.

01:19:55.410 --> 01:19:57.480
- But you also come
to these moments,

01:19:57.480 --> 01:20:01.250
and we've had one in this
election cycle, where

01:20:01.250 --> 01:20:04.820
some version of the grassroots
that is not supposed

01:20:04.820 --> 01:20:09.640
to be official conservatism
suddenly becomes politically,

01:20:09.640 --> 01:20:10.490
immensely important.

01:20:10.490 --> 01:20:10.990
Right?

01:20:10.990 --> 01:20:14.210
And I keep thinking of watching
the Republican presidential

01:20:14.210 --> 01:20:14.710
debates.

01:20:14.710 --> 01:20:17.240
And how many times did
Marco Rubio and Ted Cruz

01:20:17.240 --> 01:20:20.650
desperately explain that Donald
Trump was not a conservative

01:20:20.650 --> 01:20:22.960
in capital letters, basically.

01:20:22.960 --> 01:20:25.520
And that made a
difference to a slice

01:20:25.520 --> 01:20:27.680
of the Republican
electorate, but not enough

01:20:27.680 --> 01:20:29.960
to deny Donald Trump
the nomination.

01:20:29.960 --> 01:20:34.920
I just wanted to ask Charmaine,
as someone as someone

01:20:34.920 --> 01:20:36.940
active in a cause.

01:20:40.650 --> 01:20:42.600
The pro-life
movement is obviously

01:20:42.600 --> 01:20:44.150
a deeply political movement.

01:20:44.150 --> 01:20:45.240
Any movement would be.

01:20:45.240 --> 01:20:48.550
But it's a movement organized
around a single issue,

01:20:48.550 --> 01:20:52.990
a single philosophical position,
a single idealistic worldview.

01:20:52.990 --> 01:20:54.430
When you hear
Professor Critchlow

01:20:54.430 --> 01:20:58.630
talking about the idea that,
well, this is just politics,

01:20:58.630 --> 01:20:59.970
right?

01:20:59.970 --> 01:21:02.760
I don't mean to say
that you're downgrading

01:21:02.760 --> 01:21:04.080
idealism in any way.

01:21:04.080 --> 01:21:05.580
And when you think
about the year

01:21:05.580 --> 01:21:08.720
that religious conservatives
have just been through

01:21:08.720 --> 01:21:12.800
with Trump, I'm just curious
what your reaction is

01:21:12.800 --> 01:21:17.480
and how you see that playing
out, maybe specifically,

01:21:17.480 --> 01:21:20.300
and the different ways that
people in your movement

01:21:20.300 --> 01:21:25.180
have tried to negotiate
the rise of Donald Trump.

01:21:25.180 --> 01:21:33.260
- I think there's more strategy
among politicians than--

01:21:33.260 --> 01:21:37.550
I want to gently disagree with
Don's characterization there.

01:21:37.550 --> 01:21:41.560
I think, certainly, they
will be more caught up

01:21:41.560 --> 01:21:45.090
in the immediacy of the
tactics of whatever election

01:21:45.090 --> 01:21:46.960
happens to be in front of them.

01:21:46.960 --> 01:21:51.130
But I think that both
movements and politicians

01:21:51.130 --> 01:21:53.820
who endure for
any amount of time

01:21:53.820 --> 01:21:56.220
have to have a longer horizon.

01:21:56.220 --> 01:21:58.890
And certainly in the
pro-life movement right

01:21:58.890 --> 01:22:01.580
now, there's a lot of
ongoing conversation

01:22:01.580 --> 01:22:04.020
about what the
next horizon looks

01:22:04.020 --> 01:22:09.130
like in the wake of the June
decision in the Texas case,

01:22:09.130 --> 01:22:10.710
for example.

01:22:10.710 --> 01:22:15.660
So there will be a lot
of strategy around that.

01:22:15.660 --> 01:22:18.240
And, certainly,
following November,

01:22:18.240 --> 01:22:21.210
regardless of whether
Trump wins or Clinton wins,

01:22:21.210 --> 01:22:26.080
there'll be a much
longer horizon.

01:22:26.080 --> 01:22:28.450
- Yeah, I guess what
I'm getting at, though--

01:22:28.450 --> 01:22:34.940
not to put you on the spot-- but
there a very specific civil war

01:22:34.940 --> 01:22:38.760
over how you marry
idealism to tactics,

01:22:38.760 --> 01:22:41.300
basically with the specific
question being should

01:22:41.300 --> 01:22:45.220
pro-lifers and religious
conservatives more generally

01:22:45.220 --> 01:22:47.990
support Trump?

01:22:47.990 --> 01:22:54.950
And I guess I'm wondering--
and anyone can take this up--

01:22:54.950 --> 01:22:58.920
but from the vantage point
of 25 or 30 years from now,

01:22:58.920 --> 01:23:01.610
I mean, do you think
that this moment is

01:23:01.610 --> 01:23:05.030
a real crisis for
the movement or do

01:23:05.030 --> 01:23:08.090
you think it's one of these
political moments that

01:23:08.090 --> 01:23:11.250
will fade into the
landscape of, oh,

01:23:11.250 --> 01:23:13.950
that was sort of a tactical
debate that came and went

01:23:13.950 --> 01:23:16.230
once Trump was defeated?

01:23:16.230 --> 01:23:16.730
- No.

01:23:16.730 --> 01:23:21.200
I think that elections are
always a crack in time.

01:23:21.200 --> 01:23:23.220
They're significant.

01:23:23.220 --> 01:23:25.600
They make a difference.

01:23:25.600 --> 01:23:29.160
They are, in many ways,
an organizing structure

01:23:29.160 --> 01:23:32.060
around which we
create our history.

01:23:32.060 --> 01:23:37.440
And so it will be significant.

01:23:37.440 --> 01:23:39.240
And it does make a difference.

01:23:39.240 --> 01:23:40.990
We were talking a
little earlier, though.

01:23:40.990 --> 01:23:44.310
I think that we
can, in many ways,

01:23:44.310 --> 01:23:48.760
downgrade history by thinking
it's completely unique.

01:23:48.760 --> 01:23:52.450
We go through these cycles
in American politics.

01:23:52.450 --> 01:23:55.324
It's one of the reasons
that I study politics.

01:23:55.324 --> 01:23:57.240
I think our founders
were brilliant in the way

01:23:57.240 --> 01:24:02.130
they set up our system and that
it is resilient in its ability

01:24:02.130 --> 01:24:04.430
to reform and recreate.

01:24:04.430 --> 01:24:07.720
And I think that that is
what you will see happening.

01:24:07.720 --> 01:24:11.480
But the other thing
about elections

01:24:11.480 --> 01:24:15.090
is that the results do
matter and winning matters.

01:24:15.090 --> 01:24:17.290
And so I don't think
anybody can really

01:24:17.290 --> 01:24:21.030
tell you what's going to happen
with these different factions

01:24:21.030 --> 01:24:24.750
that have materialized and
revealed themselves until we

01:24:24.750 --> 01:24:26.070
see what the results are.

01:24:26.070 --> 01:24:29.190
Because the results
themselves will

01:24:29.190 --> 01:24:32.645
make a difference in how
people interpret what happened.

01:24:35.780 --> 01:24:41.130
- If I may, I wasn't suggesting
that ideas don't matter.

01:24:41.130 --> 01:24:45.230
I think ideas do matter.

01:24:45.230 --> 01:24:47.730
But they matter in degree.

01:24:47.730 --> 01:24:52.870
And what I was suggesting
is that the politicians who

01:24:52.870 --> 01:25:00.940
are running for office, and
they arrive at policies,

01:25:00.940 --> 01:25:03.020
it's not necessarily calculated.

01:25:03.020 --> 01:25:08.860
I'll give you two very
quick examples of this.

01:25:08.860 --> 01:25:14.200
There's a large
literature in history

01:25:14.200 --> 01:25:23.070
that Republicans in the South,
after desegregation and then

01:25:23.070 --> 01:25:29.110
integration had come,
albeit slowly and not fully,

01:25:29.110 --> 01:25:34.670
that Republican strategists
decided to tap and orchestrate

01:25:34.670 --> 01:25:39.660
campaigns against busing
and affirmative action.

01:25:39.660 --> 01:25:44.390
And that was the
way of defending

01:25:44.390 --> 01:25:48.020
this segregationist,
white privileged order.

01:25:48.020 --> 01:25:54.020
And I disagree with that kind
of narrative in this way.

01:25:54.020 --> 01:25:56.970
The Republicans were able
to win the South beginning

01:25:56.970 --> 01:26:00.630
in the 1950s on the
presidential level.

01:26:00.630 --> 01:26:05.880
And then, very gradually,
down into the local level,

01:26:05.880 --> 01:26:07.970
it was going to
be a long process.

01:26:07.970 --> 01:26:10.780
But where they
tapped into voters,

01:26:10.780 --> 01:26:14.900
was primarily Republican
voters, was in the suburbs.

01:26:14.900 --> 01:26:20.560
Newt Gingrich wasn't elected
from mule-driven, redneck

01:26:20.560 --> 01:26:27.230
farmers but from fairly
Atlantic, wealthy suburbs.

01:26:27.230 --> 01:26:30.300
The Republicans were able
to win the South primarily

01:26:30.300 --> 01:26:31.740
on the suburban vote.

01:26:31.740 --> 01:26:36.570
And, obviously, people had
moved to the suburbs, many

01:26:36.570 --> 01:26:39.950
to get away from
sunbelt suburbs,

01:26:39.950 --> 01:26:46.350
to get away from problems of the
inner city, which were racial.

01:26:46.350 --> 01:26:51.080
But the major force, I think
drive, moving to the sunbelt

01:26:51.080 --> 01:26:56.530
was better jobs, cheaper living,
cheaper houses, safer schools,

01:26:56.530 --> 01:27:00.360
and better schools
for their kids.

01:27:00.360 --> 01:27:02.550
So there was a racial component.

01:27:02.550 --> 01:27:11.990
And the anti-busing and
the anti-affirmative action

01:27:11.990 --> 01:27:17.330
sprang up in the 1970s.

01:27:17.330 --> 01:27:20.840
And Republicans decided
to tap into those issues

01:27:20.840 --> 01:27:22.850
as a way of winning elections.

01:27:22.850 --> 01:27:28.560
More to the point, Phyllis
Schlafly and her followers

01:27:28.560 --> 01:27:33.570
challenge the Republican
establishment on ERA.

01:27:33.570 --> 01:27:40.180
The Republican's leadership
from Ford, and even Reagan,

01:27:40.180 --> 01:27:44.240
although he waffled on
the issue, were pro ERA.

01:27:44.240 --> 01:27:53.370
So, as the grassroots movement
and ERA movement spread

01:27:53.370 --> 01:27:55.310
and it was learned
that you could

01:27:55.310 --> 01:28:01.420
tap into religious voters,
white women voters who got

01:28:01.420 --> 01:28:06.270
mobilized around ERA because
it had become a symbol attack

01:28:06.270 --> 01:28:11.970
on themselves, motherhood,
their roles in society,

01:28:11.970 --> 01:28:15.190
and a large buildup,
accumulation,

01:28:15.190 --> 01:28:19.250
of what they saw as attack
on their religious beliefs.

01:28:19.250 --> 01:28:22.530
Republican operatives,
at that point,

01:28:22.530 --> 01:28:25.480
who were basically outliers,
not within the party

01:28:25.480 --> 01:28:28.330
but political
strategists, decided

01:28:28.330 --> 01:28:32.400
to tap into that in order
to win the elections.

01:28:32.400 --> 01:28:34.400
That's how politics works.

01:28:34.400 --> 01:28:36.620
It's much more
complicated, as I was

01:28:36.620 --> 01:28:43.170
suggesting, than just
systematic, ideological, views.

01:28:43.170 --> 01:28:45.190
And I think that's
important to understand

01:28:45.190 --> 01:28:48.480
the dynamics of
grassroots activism

01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:52.720
and how it plays into politics.

01:28:52.720 --> 01:28:55.550
- And then, quickly-- I do want
to open it up to questions--

01:28:55.550 --> 01:28:58.440
but I guess this can be a
question for both Jennifer

01:28:58.440 --> 01:29:00.350
and Michelle in different ways.

01:29:00.350 --> 01:29:07.470
But the idea of
studying, whether it's

01:29:07.470 --> 01:29:11.610
the grassroots or
the elite ideas,

01:29:11.610 --> 01:29:13.810
I noticed Jennifer was
talking about a piece

01:29:13.810 --> 01:29:16.484
about the pro-life
movement that you liked.

01:29:16.484 --> 01:29:17.150
It was in Slate.

01:29:17.150 --> 01:29:18.850
It was written by Ruth Graham.

01:29:18.850 --> 01:29:22.700
Ruth Graham is, I believe, like
you, a graduate of Wheaton.

01:29:22.700 --> 01:29:25.130
And she's not a member
of the religious right.

01:29:25.130 --> 01:29:28.270
She's not a religious
conservative in her writing.

01:29:28.270 --> 01:29:31.087
But, as a journalist, it's
very clear to me at least,

01:29:31.087 --> 01:29:32.670
as someone who's
read her for a while,

01:29:32.670 --> 01:29:36.700
that this sympathy and
seriousness of her writing

01:29:36.700 --> 01:29:39.080
on religious issues is
informed by the fact

01:29:39.080 --> 01:29:43.180
that she has personal,
friendly, lifelong exposure

01:29:43.180 --> 01:29:46.030
to actual, evangelical
Christians.

01:29:46.030 --> 01:29:50.210
And so I wondered, both for you
as a professional conservative

01:29:50.210 --> 01:29:52.870
and for you as an academic,
studying conservatives,

01:29:52.870 --> 01:29:56.560
to what extent is the
imaginative sympathy

01:29:56.560 --> 01:29:59.880
necessary to really
write about ideas

01:29:59.880 --> 01:30:03.820
possible in the absence
of a real, lived, personal

01:30:03.820 --> 01:30:05.710
experience?

01:30:05.710 --> 01:30:08.610
And I think this is, in
certain ways, the big question

01:30:08.610 --> 01:30:13.440
for the professional Academy
with its general, liberal tilt

01:30:13.440 --> 01:30:17.300
as it approaches the study
of conservative politics

01:30:17.300 --> 01:30:18.342
and ideas.

01:30:18.342 --> 01:30:19.670
- Good question.

01:30:19.670 --> 01:30:23.270
- That was the most exciting
challenge of my research,

01:30:23.270 --> 01:30:24.790
I thought.

01:30:24.790 --> 01:30:28.040
Well, when I started,
I felt like I

01:30:28.040 --> 01:30:30.790
had two really good examples.

01:30:30.790 --> 01:30:35.060
Kristen Luker's Abortion and the
Politics of Motherhood, which

01:30:35.060 --> 01:30:39.050
was sociology when
I started, and then

01:30:39.050 --> 01:30:45.320
Jane Duhart and John Matthew's
book on the anti-ERA movement.

01:30:45.320 --> 01:30:49.560
And I have to say, Professor
Mansbridge, your work

01:30:49.560 --> 01:30:50.930
was also very influential.

01:30:50.930 --> 01:30:52.179
I think you're here somewhere.

01:30:52.179 --> 01:30:53.770
I wouldn't even recognize you.

01:30:53.770 --> 01:30:54.543
Thank you.

01:30:59.610 --> 01:31:02.720
To me, this is such
an incredible feat

01:31:02.720 --> 01:31:07.210
of scholarly imagination,
if you can put yourself

01:31:07.210 --> 01:31:13.730
in the shoes of someone who
you don't agree with at all.

01:31:13.730 --> 01:31:17.940
To me, it's incredibly rich.

01:31:17.940 --> 01:31:25.080
It's an incredible opportunity
for you as a writer,

01:31:25.080 --> 01:31:26.210
I would say.

01:31:26.210 --> 01:31:30.910
And I felt like that was
the gift of my project,

01:31:30.910 --> 01:31:34.730
that I could be given
the chance to do that.

01:31:34.730 --> 01:31:37.890
Whether I succeeded or
not, I have no idea.

01:31:37.890 --> 01:31:39.720
The only reason I
think I might have,

01:31:39.720 --> 01:31:42.710
somewhat, is I've been
in some graduate seminars

01:31:42.710 --> 01:31:46.930
where the professor would
say, OK, to the students.

01:31:46.930 --> 01:31:51.230
Do you think she's
conservative or liberal?

01:31:51.230 --> 01:31:53.880
And the students didn't know.

01:31:53.880 --> 01:31:56.890
I was like, are you kidding me?

01:31:56.890 --> 01:32:01.440
And so, I mean, at
least I fooled them.

01:32:01.440 --> 01:32:05.580
But whether I was able
to really transport

01:32:05.580 --> 01:32:10.790
the readers in the way
that I felt like Luker did

01:32:10.790 --> 01:32:15.670
or Duhart and Mathews and
Mansbridge, I don't know.

01:32:15.670 --> 01:32:20.920
But I think that if political
historians could do it

01:32:20.920 --> 01:32:23.670
and do ethnography in
that kind of way, then

01:32:23.670 --> 01:32:26.270
we'd all be very well-served.

01:32:26.270 --> 01:32:30.040
- I'll just say that
it's difficult for me

01:32:30.040 --> 01:32:33.980
to answer this outside
my voice as a scholar,

01:32:33.980 --> 01:32:39.100
doing what we hope as working
in thought leadership.

01:32:39.100 --> 01:32:43.190
I'm going to answer inevitably
from that perspective.

01:32:43.190 --> 01:32:44.930
I suppose it would
be just to tell

01:32:44.930 --> 01:32:47.770
the researchers and the
archivists out there

01:32:47.770 --> 01:32:52.710
that our sector exists, people
who came to this movement out

01:32:52.710 --> 01:32:58.580
of ideas and wanting for
the true exchange of debate

01:32:58.580 --> 01:33:00.360
on ideas.

01:33:00.360 --> 01:33:03.140
My work has nothing
to do with elections

01:33:03.140 --> 01:33:06.840
and with the political
machinations of getting 50%

01:33:06.840 --> 01:33:09.100
plus 1, those kinds of things.

01:33:09.100 --> 01:33:12.210
And so it's neither
that populist thread

01:33:12.210 --> 01:33:13.990
that ebbs and flows.

01:33:13.990 --> 01:33:17.240
It's not the how do you
do the election formula.

01:33:17.240 --> 01:33:21.140
It is day in, day out,
season in, season out ideas.

01:33:21.140 --> 01:33:25.700
And in that, anybody on my team
who's writing and I'm editing,

01:33:25.700 --> 01:33:28.290
I'm pushing them,
we don't do motives.

01:33:28.290 --> 01:33:29.500
We do ideas.

01:33:29.500 --> 01:33:32.720
I want you engaging the
ideas in what you write.

01:33:32.720 --> 01:33:33.770
We don't do ad hominum.

01:33:33.770 --> 01:33:35.390
We do ideas.

01:33:35.390 --> 01:33:40.480
And so, in that regard,
I guess, that hopefully

01:33:40.480 --> 01:33:42.540
illuminates something
that's out there

01:33:42.540 --> 01:33:50.780
as a distinct category of social
history that ought to be told.

01:33:50.780 --> 01:33:52.290
- All right.

01:33:52.290 --> 01:33:55.770
We're going to take
questions for the next--

01:33:55.770 --> 01:33:57.490
the clock is moving
and telling me

01:33:57.490 --> 01:34:02.225
exactly how long-- four
minutes and 39 seconds.

01:34:02.225 --> 01:34:04.600
- You can probably do 10 and
the fire marshall wouldn't--

01:34:04.600 --> 01:34:06.570
- The fire Marshal
wouldn't-- Oh, 13.

01:34:06.570 --> 01:34:08.525
You have just gained us 10 more.

