01:39:19.965 --> 01:39:23.660
an extraordinary collection.

01:39:23.660 --> 01:39:29.700
It needs to really attract
considerably more researchers.

01:39:29.700 --> 01:39:33.001
But just one other
very small point.

01:39:33.001 --> 01:39:36.320
One of the problems is
institutional collections,

01:39:36.320 --> 01:39:40.230
not only individual
collections but institutions.

01:39:40.230 --> 01:39:43.810
And institutions really
don't think very much

01:39:43.810 --> 01:39:45.780
in terms of archives.

01:39:45.780 --> 01:39:49.880
When I was a guest scholar,
writing my dissertation,

01:39:49.880 --> 01:39:52.900
a guest scholar on the
Brookings Institution,

01:39:52.900 --> 01:39:55.710
they actually didn't have
an archives at that point.

01:39:55.710 --> 01:40:01.120
And they had papers floating
around in the institution.

01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:06.340
And I suggested that they create
an archives, which subsequently

01:40:06.340 --> 01:40:09.020
did.

01:40:09.020 --> 01:40:14.620
But institutions don't think in
terms of historical archives.

01:40:14.620 --> 01:40:17.250
They might have
corporate archives

01:40:17.250 --> 01:40:19.190
so they could look
at correspondence,

01:40:19.190 --> 01:40:24.690
but that's, I think, a
major issue for any archives

01:40:24.690 --> 01:40:27.280
because institutions want
to protect themselves

01:40:27.280 --> 01:40:32.130
while, at the same time, they
don't think historically.

01:40:32.130 --> 01:40:37.760
I mean, the Brookings people
who are quite wonderful

01:40:37.760 --> 01:40:40.660
and gave me access
to their papers,

01:40:40.660 --> 01:40:42.720
they don't think
historically at all.

01:40:42.720 --> 01:40:47.300
And when I talked to them
about their archives-- and AEI

01:40:47.300 --> 01:40:49.250
was like this, too, by the way.

01:40:49.250 --> 01:40:53.180
Heritage came along
later-- they're like,

01:40:53.180 --> 01:40:58.000
most policy wonks are not
too interested in history,

01:40:58.000 --> 01:41:00.814
although some are
historically informed.

01:41:00.814 --> 01:41:02.480
- The danger of history
is it might show

01:41:02.480 --> 01:41:04.000
that your policy doesn't work.

01:41:04.000 --> 01:41:06.320
So you can't have that.

01:41:06.320 --> 01:41:08.380
- I might just throw
in there, there

01:41:08.380 --> 01:41:10.860
is no real shortcut to it.

01:41:10.860 --> 01:41:13.710
It's human-to-human
interaction, like anything.

01:41:13.710 --> 01:41:15.320
And it's over time.

01:41:15.320 --> 01:41:18.190
And I can't tell
you how many times

01:41:18.190 --> 01:41:23.410
you will see events where there
is no conservative included

01:41:23.410 --> 01:41:24.410
at all.

01:41:24.410 --> 01:41:28.676
And it's that layer after layer
and accretion of lack of trust.

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:37.260
There was a study the other
day showing 0% Republicans

01:41:37.260 --> 01:41:42.130
and I don't know in
some political science

01:41:42.130 --> 01:41:43.330
something or other.

01:41:43.330 --> 01:41:46.740
So things like
this is if you just

01:41:46.740 --> 01:41:49.330
need to be really intentional.

01:41:49.330 --> 01:41:51.540
Particularly, at
lunch time, we were

01:41:51.540 --> 01:41:56.460
talking about how technology
can separate and divide us.

01:41:56.460 --> 01:41:59.950
There's this increasing
problem of having your silos

01:41:59.950 --> 01:42:05.820
and your filter bubbles online.

01:42:05.820 --> 01:42:07.870
None of us are getting
as much information

01:42:07.870 --> 01:42:10.710
that comes at us because
we do have more choice now.

01:42:10.710 --> 01:42:12.780
So we have to be
much more intentional

01:42:12.780 --> 01:42:15.810
in our personal news gathering.

01:42:15.810 --> 01:42:19.160
But I would say that's the
same analogy for you in terms

01:42:19.160 --> 01:42:25.140
of you're trying to resist
this increasing balkanization

01:42:25.140 --> 01:42:28.310
that we have in our
culture because everybody

01:42:28.310 --> 01:42:32.570
has so much choice
in what they consume.

