01:47:59.910 --> 01:48:02.364
with permission from
the powers that be.

01:48:02.364 --> 01:48:03.280
- Thank you very much.

01:48:03.280 --> 01:48:06.270
I'm a 45-year-old mother
of three daughters.

01:48:06.270 --> 01:48:09.300
And I want to thank
you all for this panel.

01:48:09.300 --> 01:48:13.360
I saw the billboard up on
the midst of Harvard yard,

01:48:13.360 --> 01:48:16.250
amidst my lunch
hour during work.

01:48:16.250 --> 01:48:19.890
And I'd like to speak because
abortion, I don't really think,

01:48:19.890 --> 01:48:23.300
falls between,
necessarily, party lines.

01:48:23.300 --> 01:48:27.770
Because life circumstances
can reach a vortex.

01:48:27.770 --> 01:48:33.180
And it can create a very
difficult and complex

01:48:33.180 --> 01:48:35.320
confluence of circumstances.

01:48:35.320 --> 01:48:37.660
And what I would
like to speak to

01:48:37.660 --> 01:48:41.310
is how there is a barbell
effect within abortion

01:48:41.310 --> 01:48:44.870
within our country that
no one wants to discuss.

01:48:44.870 --> 01:48:47.650
And if we're going to talk
about archival records,

01:48:47.650 --> 01:48:50.870
where are the
archives of those who

01:48:50.870 --> 01:48:52.240
have been through abortions?

01:48:52.240 --> 01:48:56.660
Because abortion in our society
is considered forbidden grief.

01:48:56.660 --> 01:48:58.850
It is not one that
can be vocalized.

01:48:58.850 --> 01:49:02.240
It is not one that you can talk
about in public with friends.

01:49:02.240 --> 01:49:07.370
It is not one that is for
open dinner discussion.

01:49:07.370 --> 01:49:12.170
It's not even one where, in
the pulpits of our churches,

01:49:12.170 --> 01:49:16.150
nationwide, our own
religious leaders

01:49:16.150 --> 01:49:20.070
feel comfortable addressing the
constituents and parishioners

01:49:20.070 --> 01:49:22.180
within our diocese.

01:49:22.180 --> 01:49:32.450
So it's a very multi-faceted
and, obviously, complex

01:49:32.450 --> 01:49:36.730
condition and
tragic circumstance.

01:49:36.730 --> 01:49:42.330
But the barbell effect, the
end result, is the same.

01:49:42.330 --> 01:49:46.680
For those abortions that
occur between 18 and 25,

01:49:46.680 --> 01:49:48.930
it's usually from many
different circumstances

01:49:48.930 --> 01:49:52.070
than for those that
occur between 35 and 50.

01:49:52.070 --> 01:49:53.540
And if you study
abortions, you'll

01:49:53.540 --> 01:49:57.050
see that there's a great
number in that bracket that

01:49:57.050 --> 01:50:01.340
fall towards single women
that it's not for them.

01:50:01.340 --> 01:50:04.020
They don't want to have
a child and they're

01:50:04.020 --> 01:50:08.240
pursuing their collegiate
career and academics.

01:50:08.240 --> 01:50:09.660
And then it thins out.

01:50:09.660 --> 01:50:12.200
And then you have
fetal abnormalities.

01:50:12.200 --> 01:50:15.870
You have family make-up.

01:50:15.870 --> 01:50:19.200
There can be gender
discrimination that goes on

01:50:19.200 --> 01:50:23.530
within a family if it's a family
of, say, three boys or two

01:50:23.530 --> 01:50:27.700
boys or three girls and there's
an unexpected pregnancy.

01:50:27.700 --> 01:50:31.120
And these are real
issues that no one is--

01:50:31.120 --> 01:50:32.600
- They are, indeed.

01:50:32.600 --> 01:50:35.840
I'm just wondering if there's
one particular aspect,

01:50:35.840 --> 01:50:39.160
if it's the archival aspect,
the nature of stories

01:50:39.160 --> 01:50:41.420
and narratives about the
experience of abortion

01:50:41.420 --> 01:50:43.935
that I could just have
the panel address.

01:50:43.935 --> 01:50:44.980
Would that be the issue?

01:50:44.980 --> 01:50:45.520
- Yes.

01:50:45.520 --> 01:50:49.021
I would like to know where
these archives are held.

01:50:49.021 --> 01:50:49.520
- OK.

01:50:49.520 --> 01:50:52.350
Well, if I could just--
both that specific

01:50:52.350 --> 01:50:54.980
question but also more,
generally, for anyone,

01:50:54.980 --> 01:51:00.420
anyone on the panel-- I
think the issue of abortion,

01:51:00.420 --> 01:51:02.990
in particular, so
much of this surface

01:51:02.990 --> 01:51:07.840
political debate coexists
with these hidden stories

01:51:07.840 --> 01:51:09.400
or stories that exist.

01:51:09.400 --> 01:51:11.540
In my personal
experience, I would

01:51:11.540 --> 01:51:13.780
say I encounter the
most stories of abortion

01:51:13.780 --> 01:51:18.520
either in very explicitly
feminist writing

01:51:18.520 --> 01:51:22.060
or very explicitly
regretful project,

01:51:22.060 --> 01:51:25.240
Rachel-style, pro-life writing.

01:51:25.240 --> 01:51:27.570
Those are the two
places, both of them

01:51:27.570 --> 01:51:30.820
clearly outside the
mainstream media.

01:51:30.820 --> 01:51:32.200
But, please.

01:51:32.200 --> 01:51:35.470
- And I was going to say, unless
historians can correct me,

01:51:35.470 --> 01:51:40.900
but we don't have
much documentation

01:51:40.900 --> 01:51:48.250
in US women's and gender history
on what you're talking about.

01:51:48.250 --> 01:51:50.850
There is a book coming out with
the University of California

01:51:50.850 --> 01:51:56.110
Press by Jennifer Holland on
the history of abortion crisis

01:51:56.110 --> 01:51:57.970
centers.

01:51:57.970 --> 01:52:00.430
It's not going to be out
in the next year or so.

01:52:00.430 --> 01:52:06.120
But there is coverage of much
of the experience and testimony

01:52:06.120 --> 01:52:08.240
that you're talking about.

01:52:08.240 --> 01:52:11.420
And it does fill
in some of this gap

01:52:11.420 --> 01:52:14.450
in the historical literature.

01:52:14.450 --> 01:52:17.890
But because of the
problem of the fact

01:52:17.890 --> 01:52:24.440
that we can't access medical
records where women talk

01:52:24.440 --> 01:52:26.870
about these things,
it's really only going

01:52:26.870 --> 01:52:30.070
to be in those places
where women have testified,

01:52:30.070 --> 01:52:35.940
often in intimate or
religious settings,

01:52:35.940 --> 01:52:40.200
where we can find their voices.

01:52:40.200 --> 01:52:43.690
And it represents a challenge
to us as a historical community.

01:52:43.690 --> 01:52:49.130
I don't know of any
historical archival sources.

01:52:49.130 --> 01:52:50.560
And I'm--

01:52:50.560 --> 01:52:56.190
- And my question is because
do they not exist for a reason?

01:52:56.190 --> 01:52:58.910
And, secondly, I'd
like to just say

01:52:58.910 --> 01:53:02.360
that I admire the
course and topic

01:53:02.360 --> 01:53:04.950
of the paper, the dissertation,
that you have to give.

01:53:04.950 --> 01:53:10.190
And as it pertains to our
Republican-forced candidate

01:53:10.190 --> 01:53:12.680
